# Codex Reviewer Findings — ПССК Prompt Quality Review
Chain: pssk-som-b2-1-260416-v5-260416-145535-15fd

## Issues Found
1. [CRITICAL] Fix B leaves the completed card able to close the current open session — The prompt splits one table into multiple cards, but its B.1 object shape still assigns `openSessionId: openSessionByTableId[tableId]?.id || null` to every table group, including closed-session groups. In the real code, the close action reads `group.openSessionId` first and falls back to bulk-closing group orders (`staffordersmobile.jsx:2164-2177`), while the button is rendered for any table card with `onCloseTable` and orders (`staffordersmobile.jsx:2390`). Following the prompt as written can let the old completed card close the new active session or trigger the fallback on the wrong card. PROMPT FIX: Add a required Fix B step that gates the close-table affordance to the current open-session card only, for example by passing `onCloseTable` only when `group.sessionId === openSessionByTableId[group.id]?.id`, and explicitly state that completed-session cards must not expose the close action.

2. [CRITICAL] Fix B ignores session-unsafe request UI inside `OrderGroupCard` — The prompt says not to modify `OrderGroupCard` internals, but that component derives `tableRequests` purely by `group.id` / `tableId` (`staffordersmobile.jsx:1875-1878`) and uses it for status, blockers, summary chips, and request actions (`staffordersmobile.jsx:1129-1139`, `2073-2100`, `2148-2157`, `2378`). After B.1, both the closed and open cards keep the same `group.id = tableId`, so both cards will surface the current table's active requests even though only the open-session card should. PROMPT FIX: Expand Fix B scope to make request rendering session-aware. Either pass prefiltered requests per group from the parent, or update `OrderGroupCard` logic so request UI/actions only appear on the current open-session card, using `request.table_session` when available and `group.sessionId`/`openSessionByTableId` as the contract.

3. [MEDIUM] Fix B.6 still depends on stale `openSessions`, so the banner race is not actually closed — The prompt’s new `handleBannerNavigate` resolves `tableId -> compositeKey` only through `openSessionByTableId`. But BUG-SM-015 is exactly the window where the new order already exists while `openSessions` is stale; in that state the new card can already be formed from `order.table_session`, while `openSessionByTableId` still points nowhere. The proposed handler can therefore resolve to `tableId__no-session` or no DOM node if the user taps the banner immediately. PROMPT FIX: Change B.6 to resolve from the current grouped data first, preferring the current active/new session card for that table, and use `openSessionByTableId` only as a fallback. If that is intentionally out of scope, soften S3 from a guaranteed outcome to a best-effort outcome.

4. [MEDIUM] Two verification facts still do not match the current source file — The prompt says the orders query has `staleTime: 0`, but the actual orders query block at `staffordersmobile.jsx:3496-3510` has no `staleTime` at all. The Fix C verification also expects `const queryClient = useQueryClient()` to have exactly 1 hit, but the real file has three hits at lines 1581, 1749, and 2883. These mismatches can make a correct implementation look suspicious and cause unnecessary STOP/escalation. PROMPT FIX: Remove the nonexistent `orders` `staleTime: 0` note, and rewrite the `queryClient` check so it anchors the main component scope specifically instead of requiring a global 1-hit count.

5. [LOW] The prompt still has internal guardrail inconsistencies that can cause hesitation — B.5 allows optional comment-only `data-group-id` edits at `~565` and `~1173`, but the final Safety Guards later say the diff should touch only 8 locations and only count the live `~2292` site. The prompt also says Fix C depends on `group.sessionId` from Fix B.1, but the provided Fix C code does not use `group.sessionId` at all. PROMPT FIX: Either forbid comment-only edits outright or update the Safety Guard to tolerate those extra documentation-only hunks, and correct the Fix C dependency note to say it is complementary to Fix B, not code-dependent on it.

